Architecture plan for `mike-t-oznn-super-cool-tools`

Issue set

- `#43 Include tool crates in Tailwind content scan`

Module structure and file organization

- `tailwind.config.js`
  Source of truth for Tailwind content scanning. This is the primary file for
  the issue because the purge/content configuration currently covers the shell
  but not tool crates.
- `crates/toolbox-shell/styles/app.css`
  Shared Tailwind entry stylesheet compiled by the Trunk pre-build hook.
- `crates/tools/**`
  Tool crates may embed Tailwind utility classes directly in Rust-rendered HTML.
  The calculator in `crates/tools/calculator/src/lib.rs` is the current example.
- `xtask/src/main.rs`
  Build orchestrator used to regenerate the shell bundle and packaged tools via
  `cargo xtask build`.
- `docs/ADDING_A_TOOL.md`
  Should mention that tool-crate Rust files need to stay within the Tailwind
  content scan so utility classes are preserved in production CSS.

Dependencies between issues

- Only issue `#43` is in scope for this batch.
- It depends on the existing shell/tool architecture already merged:
  - Trunk + Tailwind pipeline
  - calculator tool crate
  - `cargo xtask build`
  - developer guide in `docs/ADDING_A_TOOL.md`

Key design decisions

- Treat tool crates as first-class Tailwind content sources. The content scan
  must include `./crates/tools/**/*.rs` so runtime-rendered tool markup keeps
  its utility classes in the final CSS bundle.
- Keep the fix centralized in `tailwind.config.js`. No per-tool workaround or
  duplicated safelist should be introduced when one content-path update solves
  the root problem.
- Validate through the real packaging path with `cargo xtask build`, because
  that is what emits the CSS bundle consumed by deployed shells.
- Use the calculator as the verification target: the expected result is the
  normal four-column keypad layout instead of a vertically stacked, purged-CSS
  rendering.
